Types:

COMESTIBLES
% is food as usual
" is condiments! Similar to potions or herbs.
! is potion

READABLES
? is scroll as usual.
+ is spellbook

WEARABLES
= is ring
] is armour
[ is er...
) is weapon (bladed only??)
} is ranged weapon?
These are likely wrong. Must compare Nethack, Adom, Omega, Zangband
to see what they use for each.
& is amulet?? Maybe not.

 Here's what the others use:
ROGUE: ]=armour, )=weapon/ranged/missile, = =ring,
   /=staff/wand. [,(, {} are not defined. No amulets?  %=stairs (down).
   #=passage

NH:    )=weapon, [=any armour:suit/shield/helmet/gloves/etc
   (=tool, [=suit/armour   (]=mimic), {}=scenery (water/fountain)
   "=amulet/web, &=demon. /=wand,  <=stairs up  >=stairs down (GOOD)
   #=passage

ADOM: #=wall, /=open door, &=forge/other feature, = =water
      [=any armour/shield?   \=wand,  (=weapon,
      }=missile weapon, /=missile, ]=tool. {=music instmnt.
      = =ring, "=book, ' =neckwear, ~=bracers (surely are armour?)
      ) doesn't represent anything? &= feature/forest/demon!
      <=stairs up, >=stairs down. (GOOD)

OMEGA: |=open door, -=closed door, #=wall, "=hedge, *=heap, 1-0=features
   )=weapon, (=missile weapon,    ]=suit of armour, [=shield,
   }=cloak,  {=pair of boots, = =ring. No helmets! No sign of missiles
   for the missile weapons? no amulets.  /=stick (as in wand?)

ZANG: |=blade, /=polearm/axe,  \=hafted (mace),
  (=armour/cloak, )=shield, ]=head,gloves,boots, [=hard armour.
  }=missile weapon, {=missile.  ,=food...
  = =ring,   "=amulet  &=chest! ~=other tool (incl junk)
  -=wand/rod _=staff   <=stairs up >=stairs down   #=wall
  %=mineral vein/tree *=buried treasure.
CRAWL (blurgh): #=wall, <=up, >=down(GOOD).
  )=weapon (sword,dagger,club,spear,mace, axe)...
  )=missiles (arrows,darts,needles,bolts,stones),
  )=missile weapons (blowgun)  do we see a pattern here? ;)
  [=armour(robe,leather armour),
  %=food/corpse
  "=amulet
(End of comparison of other roguelikes)

So, here's my opinion: ) is almost always a weapon (when it is used).
 Armour wants to be either [ or ], and in order to correspond to
 weapon, it ought to be ]. That agrees with omega and rogue, only
 vaguely with angband (] is other armour not main armour), but is
 at odds with Adom and Nethack. Unfortunately.
 = probably ought to be *any* jewelery or accessories. Perhaps.
 / ought to be wands, agreeing with near everything except angband
 (and opposite to Adom). whilst - ought to be missiles rather than
 walls???
 Should we have separate types of armour by different symbols?
 I think they would at most be divided into suits and "the rest".
 } ought to be missile weapons?
 Now, we have (, [, {.  One of these ought to be tools. Maybe one
 ought to be "non-suit armour", maybe one should be shields???
 Something should be containers: I don't think they should be
 lumped in with tools.
 "non-suit armour" other than shields ought to be represented by some
 sort of symbol that indicates a certain *smallness* as those items
 are pretty small...    ...But I can't find such a symbol :P
 & symbol wants to be used by something... Adom uses it for lots
 of stuff (forges, forests, demons!), NH uses it for demons, angband
 for chests, Omega for artifacts?! I feel inclined to maybe
 use it either for tools or small armour or features?
 Dont know what to do with \ (not wand!). | prolly should be rods (or staves).

 Alternative groupings:
   group all armour together.
   group suit+shield together, the rest(other) together.
   suit is exclusive, shield+other together. (suit is biggest).
   shield is exclusive, suit+other together. (shield is wielded, rest worn).
   suit exclusive, shield exclusive, the rest together.
   every type separate. (one is not really a substitute for another!)
  -I don't *really* want more than 2 groups for armour, there's not enough
   symbols.


 Here's another spin on this:
   (=shield           )=weapon   (both normally wielded)
   [=suit             ]=container      &=tool
   {=other armour     }=missile weapon -=missile
   armour             wieldables (apart from container..)
   left hand          right hand

  It has a certain something. But stops [] being associated with armour:(
  Still don't have a role for \ symbol, nor '

 _ wants to be altars. We SHALL have them. < stairs up, > stairs down,
 as with near any other SANE roguelike. Very few have them the other
 way round.

